# DEEP DIVE: [What the Times Missed About Unschooling](https://opened.co/blog/you-can-do-this-what-the-new-york-times-misses-about-unschooling)

Last Sunday, the New York Times just published a guest essay titled, "[The Home-Schooled Kids Are Not All Right](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/12/14/opinion/home-school-isolation.html)" - a pretty sweeping claim based on the author's (admittedly awful) experience. Stefan Merrill Block describes a childhood of isolation, a struggling mother, and unmet childhood needs. Understandably, he doesn't want other kids to go through that.

His pain is real. And he makes points worth hearing: isolation can harm children, some kids fall through the cracks, and adults outside the home sometimes see what parents miss.

But then he calls for mandatory registration, assessments, and check-ins for all homeschoolers. This argument rests on a comparison between his experience and a system that would have caught his pain. Teachers who would have noticed. Counselors who would have helped.

That school system doesn't exist.

In his response, Isaac Morehouse points out that this is a good example of the [Nirvana Fallacy](https://opened.co/blog/you-can-do-this-what-the-new-york-times-misses-about-unschooling): comparing a real situation to an imagined ideal. It's worth noting that three weeks before this essay, the same New York Times published another article: "[America's Children Are Unwell. Are Schools Part of the Problem?](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/11/24/magazine/youth-mental-health-crisis-schools.html)" Their own data showed 1 in 4 teenage boys now diagnosed with ADHD, anxiety spiking as early as age 6.

[Peter Gray](https://petergray.substack.com/), a research professor at Boston College, has tracked this for years: every fall when school starts, teen mental health tanks. ER visits for anxiety spike. Psychiatric hospitalizations rise. Summer comes and it improves. When researchers asked teenagers what stresses them out, [83% cited school](https://opened.co/blog/every-august-youth-mental-health-crises-spike-every-june-they-plummet-its-not-a-coincidence). Nothing else came close.

As Peter Gray puts it: "Instead of saying, 'We need to fix the schools,' the message is, 'We need to fix the kids.'"

[Dr. Claire Honeycutt](https://x.com/home) responded to the NY Times article saying, "The biggest problem in education today is the assumption that there is one perfect way to learn that suits all children everywhere under all conditions. That's never been true. No single school - or education model will fit all kids. The biggest gift we can give future generations is freedom. Freedom to not be confined to a single, failing system. The New York Times doesn't know my children or my neighbor's children. How can they possibly know what's best for my kids? They can't. We were a far better educated country before we tried to strip out all individuation and uniqueness out of our citizenry. Our best teachers leave because they are no longer allowed to fit the way they teach to their classrooms. If you want people to return to public school, make it something worth returning to. Until then, let the parents who are upending their entire lives to be with their children do their work in peace.

They are not the problem."

Our message to parents is simpler: you don't have to be a perfect parent to do better than the status quo if school is failing your kid.

If rigid one-size-fits-all schooling represents one end of the spectrum, unschooling represents the other. Like any approach, it can be done well or poorly. But with a safe, supportive environment, you might be surprised how little coercion and formal curriculum is required to let your kid thrive.

So what does unschooling look like when it's done right?

Amanda Schenkenberger, an OpenEd mom and homeschool coach [recently interviewed on Fox News](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8jCQcIZQWc), put it simply: "Unschooling is pursuing a level of learning and following my kids' lead to what they're curious about and diving deeply into the subject as long as their curiosity is alive about it."

As OpenEd students, her boys take Oregon's required standardized tests and score in the top 10 percent nationally. But test scores aren't really the point. The real argument for unschooling is that kids who drive their own learning actually want to learn - and that changes everything.

