# TOOLS WE'RE BOOKMARKING

[Savvy Learning](https://savvylearning.com/) - Personalized reading and math instruction in 25-minute sessions, 4x/week. From this week's podcast guest. Meets kids where they are. (OpenEd Marketplace)

[Writey the Whiteboard](https://writeyboards.com/) - Peel-and-stick whiteboards. Mark Cuban-backed. $30 for a 2x3 sheet. No drilling, repositionable. Math problems, spelling words, mapping your teenager's life decisions - a whiteboard handles all of it. (Writey)

[The Feynman Technique](https://educatedandfree.substack.com/p/teach-yourself-anything-using-feynmans-technique) - Richard Feynman had a simple method for learning anything: try to explain it to a child. If you can't, you don't understand it well enough. Go back and study the parts you stumbled on. Then try again. Four steps: choose a topic, explain it simply, identify gaps, revise. Works for parents learning alongside their kids and for kids tackling something new. (Educated and Free)

[History Odyssey Timeline](https://pandiapress.com/collections/timelines/products/history-odyssey-timeline) - Four timeline posters, 5 feet long each, where students enter historical events across 7 categories - Men and Women, Wars and Conflicts, Treaties and Agreements, and more. Visual learners love having history literally unfold in front of them. Can hang on the wall or fold into a binder. (Pandia Press)

[From Hillsdale to Homeschooling](https://k12blog.hillsdale.edu/from-hillsdale-to-homeschooling-part-ii-advice-from-homeschooling-alumnae/) - Practical advice from three Hillsdale alumnae with 30 combined years of homeschooling. Build community through co-ops. Let your calendar match your family - not the public school's. And learn to tell the difference between "can't" and "won't" when your kid says something's too hard. (Hillsdale K-12)

[Navigating Holidays with Intense Kids](https://raisinglifelonglearners.com/navigating-the-holidays-with-intense-and-sensitive-kids/) - Colleen Kessler's guide for families with neurodivergent kids. Bring favorite snacks. Have an exit strategy. Let go of other people's expectations. "You didn't cause this. Their intensity isn't your failure." (Raising Lifelong Learners)

[11 Things to Hear This Winter](https://ahumbleplace.com/things-to-hear-winter/) - Dallas Lore Sharp's nature study list from the early 1900s, still worth reading today. The three great silences of winter. The voice of the north wind through pine trees. The tinkle of water under thin ice. Chickadees in empty woods. Simple goals that turn noticing into a habit. (A Humble Place)

[Free Kindergarten Resources](https://www.reddit.com/r/homeschool/comments/1po697d/free_kindergarten_resources/) - A Reddit thread with community-sourced recommendations for budget-conscious families. Real parents sharing what actually worked. (r/homeschool)

### From the Podcast: Janssen's Favorite Read-Alouds

The [Penderwicks series](https://www.amazon.com/Penderwicks-Summer-Sisters-Rabbit-General/dp/0440420474) - five books about four sisters that her kids have listened to "15 or 20 times, maybe more." They call each other by the characters' names. [Nanny Piggins](https://www.amazon.com/Nanny-Piggins-R-Spratt/dp/0316068195) - an outrageously weird Australian series for kids who like Wayside School or Mrs. Piggle-Wiggle. And for screen-free listening, she recommends the [Yoto Player](https://us.yotoplay.com/).

